 When they had left, Baca walked out of the house unharmed.
 After the saloon was destroyed by a fire and rebuilt in 1879, it burned down again in 1899, causing Swearengen to leave the town.
Alma is an unincorporated community in Catron County, New Mexico, United States, north of Glenwood and south of Reserve.
As a result of relative lack of water and quick wooden construction, Tombstone experienced major fires in June 1881 and May 1882.
thumb|350px|'L' and 'O' counties, Cherokee Outlet, 1894
The earliest saloons were often nothing more than tents or shacks that served homemade whiskey that included such ingredients as “raw alcohol, burnt sugar and .
In the late 1880s, the Rock Island Railroad built a rail line into Indian Territory, entering near Caldwell, Kansas, and following the Chisholm Trail.
 At part of the infrastructure, the company established railroad stations near several of the existing stage stations along the trail.
 . . chewing tobacco” and was known by such names as “Tanglefoot, Forty-Rod, Tarantula Juice, Taos Lightning, Red Eye, and Coffin Varnish.” Other offerings included “Cactus Wine, made from a mix of tequila and peyote tea, and Mule Skinner, made with whiskey and blackberry liquor.
 Two of the stations, Pond Creek, built at Pond Stage Stand on Round Pond Creek, and Enid, built at Skeleton Station near the Skeleton Ranch headquarters, would became involved in a controversy between the railroad and the Department of the Interior.
 The house rotgut was often 100 proof, though it was sometimes cut by the barkeep with turpentine, ammonia, gun powder or cayenne”. Some saloons prided themselves on homemade beer and it was not always served at room temperature.
 In July 1865, the route via the Smoky Hill River was surveyed and soon thereafter coaches were in operation. Ben Holladay, acting for a competing organization, bought the Butterfield Overland Despatch in March 1866, when Eastern express companies threatened to take it over and establish a service between the Missouri River and Sacramento, California.
By way of entertainment, saloons offered dancing girls dressed in somewhat-revealing strapless dresses with feather boas, some of whom occasionally or routinely doubled as prostitutes (these girls were often addressed as 'Miss ___').
