To avoid the rocky and mountainous Raton Pass, wagon traffic used the Cimarron Cutoff of the Santa Fe Trail during the 1840s.
 Thereafter, Mountain Branch near Raton Pass became more popular with traders, immigrants, gold-seekers, and government supply trains.
South of Cimarron is Palisades Sill, with high cliffs surrounding a modest flow of the Cimarron River.
